This document should specify how to pass binary data to mongodb.

From looking through the code of GridFS it seems that binary data is passed to mongo by using scalar references:

{code}
"field" => \$blbo
{code}

GridFS actually does a {{{bless(\$data)}}} but I think the bless is irrelevant. (I haven't test this as I was just helping someone out in IRC.)

Looking closer at perl_mongo.c I see that it will also be passed as binary data if the string contains en embedded null by this if: {{{if (sv_len (sv) != strlen (SvPV_nolen (sv)))}}}

I've just seen that you had to change the anonymous type constraint used for
the timeout attribute in Connection.pm as it was causing problems:

http://github.com/mongodb/mongo-perl-driver/commit/c0ef67ef2286a2ee57d1d542f30f57805e423b3a

It's strange that this needed fixing as it is just what
http://search.cpan.org/~flora/Moose-0.99/lib/Moose/Manual/Types.pod#ANONYMOUS_TYPES
says how an anonymous subtype should be created.

However by changing that to a 'non-anonymous' subtype it is now globally
visible and afaik this could cause problems when someone has a 'Natural' type
constraint defined somewhere in their codebase. For example the following code
doesn't work now:

---------------------------

package Foo;

use Any::Moose;
use Any::Moose 'Util::TypeConstraints';

subtype 'Natural' => as 'Int' => where { $_ > 0 };

has foo => (
	is => 'rw',
	isa => 'Natural'
);

package main;

use MongoDB;

MongoDB::Connection->new();

---------------------------

I don't know what the best solution would be, but the easiest is probably to
change the 'Natural' in Connection.pm to something like 'MongoDB::Timeout' so
that it's at least a name that is unlikely to be used somewhere else. Although
it will still be globally visible.

Alternatively the 'isa' could be made 'Int'  again and the validity check could be moved into the C module.

So I'm trying to write some fault tolerance in my script to handle when a mongod instance goes down, and I've noticed that I often get the following error:

    (in cleanup) can't get db response, not connected at ...

which is not trappable at any useful point as far as I can tell. I believe it is happening when the cursor is being demolished (obviously it occurs only when a connection is broken).

I.e. consider the following script, where you shutdown mongod during execution.. 

  #!/usr/bin/perl

  use strict;
  use warnings;

  use MongoDB;

  my $conn = MongoDB::Connection->new( host => '127.0.0.1', port => '27017' );
  my $db = $conn->get_database('test');
  my $coll = $db->get_collection('disconnect_test');

  print "Shutdown mongod then hit enter...\n"; getc(STDIN);

  eval {
    # trap immediate "bad response" type errors
    my $doc = $coll->find_one({ 'foo' => 'bar' });
  };

  # more often than not, the "cleanup" error will occur somewhere from here on...

  print "done\n";


