Documentation and comments suggest that the perl driver guards against insertion of strings that are not valid UTF-8. There seems to be one unfortunate case where that isn't so, namely when a non-valid UTF-8 string happens to have its utf8 flag set. 

It seems that while the driver recognizes non-UTF8 strings, it relies on SvPVutf8 to supply a valid utf8 alternative, which fails in this particular case (see below).

Would it be possible to recheck the return value of SvPVutf8 and throw an error in case it happens to still be invalid, to guard against these cases?

{code}
#!/usr/bin/env perl

use Encode;
use Devel::Peek;

use Inline C => <<END_C;
char *utf8get(SV *sv) {
	STRLEN len;
	char *str = SvPVutf8(sv, len);
	return str;
}
END_C

for (0..1) {
	my $do = ($_) ? "doesn't" : "does";
	print "\n***What one $do expect.\n";
	my $s = "R\xe9sum\xe9"; 
	Dump($s);
	if ($_) {
		Encode::_utf8_on($s); 
	}
	$s = utf8get($s);
	Dump($s);
}
