Requests to the web application sometimes fail due to MongoDB Perl driver throwing exceptions. Exception messages include:

- invalid header received at /usr/local/perl5/lib/site_perl/5.14.2/x86_64-linux/MongoDB/Cursor.pm line 260.
- missed the response we wanted, please try again at /usr/local/perl5/lib/site_perl/5.14.2/x86_64-linux/MongoDB/Cursor.pm line 260.
- can't get db response, not connected at /usr/local/perl5/lib/site_perl/5.14.2/x86_64-linux/MongoDB/Cursor.pm line 260.

We have been running test clients that hit the server with typical user sessions an average of four times per minute. We leave the test clients running for hours or days. These failures happen intermittently.

These failures do NOT occur when the application runs under CGI. They occur only when the application runs under mod_perl.

The application caches and reuses the database object, which is itself created on first use with:


      my $connection = MongoDB::Connection->new(host           => $MONGO_HOST, 
                                                port           => $MONGO_PORT, 
                                                query_timeout  => 60000,
                                                timeout        => 60000,
                                                auto_reconnect => 1,
                                                auto_connect   => 1,
                                                )
         or fatal_error "Can't connect to MongoDB";
      $DATABASE = $connection->get_database($MONGO_DB);

I wrapped all MongoDB calls in eval to try to localize exactly where the exceptions are being thrown. It's somewhere in this (slightly obfuscated) code:


      my $collection = $DATABASE->get_collection($collection_name);
      my $cursor = $collection->find(\%param);

      foreach my $result ($cursor->all)
         {
         my $object  = {};
         $object->{one}      = $result->{one};
         $object->{mongo_id} = $result->{_id}->to_string;
         foreach my $key (@KEYS)
            {
            $object->{$key} = $result->{$key} if exists $result->{$key};
            }

         push @results, $object; 
         }

It's hard to know for sure, but it seems that the line '$object->{one} = $result->{one};' is what always throws the exception.

I added a line '$cursor->immortal(1);' and it SEEMED to reduce, but not eliminate, the exceptions.

We're getting an exception thrown (without the immortal line show above) about 5% to 10% of the client test runs. Test runs average about 30 requests, each, so we're getting an exception on average about one out of every 300-600 requests.

The failures sometimes come in clusters of half a dozen client runs in a row, at other times are isolated.

Hello,

We store a lot (millions) of files in a GridFS database. In order to iterate (and resume iterating) over a list of those files sorted rougly by an insertion date, we do this:

{code:perl}
# Create a cursor to iterate over files
# ('query_timeout' is set to 19000 ms, we can't affort to wait 30 seconds)
my $find_query = { _id => { '$gt' => MongoDB::OID->new(value => '...') } };
my $cursor = $mongodb_fs_files_collection->query($find_query)->sort( {_id => 1} )->fields( {_id => 1, filename => 1} );
$cursor->immortal(1);
{code}

We were having a lot of problems with {{recv timed out}} previously (Perl driver seems to fail when MongoDB decides to create a new 2 GB data file for a minute or so), so we wrapped attempts to fetch a next object into {{eval{};}} that also retries to read a next filename:

{code:perl}
my $attempt_to_read_succeeded = 0;

for ( my $retry = 0 ; $retry < 3 ; ++$retry )
{
    if ( $retry > 0 )
    {
        WARN("Retrying ($retry)...");
    }

    eval {

        # Read next
        $object = $cursor->next;
        $attempt_to_read_succeeded = 1;
    };

    if ( $@ )
    {
        WARN("Attempt to read next the filename didn't succeed because: $@");
    }
    else
    {
        last;
    }
}

unless ( $attempt_to_read_succeeded )
{
    LOGDIE("Unable to read the next filename from GridFS.");
}
{code}

However, we found out that when an attempt to read a next object from the cursor ({{$object = $cursor->next;}}) fails with {{recv timed out}}, the cursor skips a chunk of objects in the cursor's sequence (~94,000 in our case) and then resumes returning objects just fine.

Wat do? Is it safe to continue using the cursor (without recreating it) after it {{die()}} s? How do we prevent those {{recv timed out}} failures from happening?

